<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,509,1038]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,617,642]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The species differs from the two closest species 
<taxonomicName authority="Meinert, 1868" authorityName="Meinert" authorityYear="1868" box="[871,1242,617,642]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Megaphyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sjaelandicum">
<emphasis box="[871,1057,617,641]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">M. sjaelandicum</emphasis>
(Meinert, 
<number box="[1177,1234,617,642]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="1868.0">1868</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Attems, 1907" authorityName="Attems" authorityYear="1907" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Megaphyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tauricum">
<emphasis box="[1297,1436,618,641]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">M. tauricum</emphasis>
(Attems, 
<number box="[255,312,654,678]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="1907.0">1907</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
by the more widely rounded and simple promere without lobes or indentation (
<figureCitation box="[1213,1340,653,678]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 a – g" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[171,1417,489,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[169,1423,483,1688]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 16 a – g. Megaphyllum rhodopinum. Male from near Shabran Peak, Slavyanka Mt., Bulgaria: (16 a) gonopods, posterior view; (16 b) right gonopods, mesal view; (16 c) right opisthomere, meso-posterior view; (16 d) right opisthomere, lateral view. Males from near Proastio, Kavala county, Greece: penis form (16 e) posterior and (16 f) left lateral views, (16 f *) another penis, right lateral view. Female from the first locality: (16 g) left vulva, posterior view (setae omitted). Abbreviations: ah: anterior hump; ap: anterior process, asp: anterior process of the solenomere, ca: central ampulla, ct: connecting tube; h: hump, op: operculum, pa: posterior ampulla, pp: posterior process, psp: posterior process of the solenomere, P: promere. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223788/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
Figs 
<number box="[1270,1298,653,678]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="16.0">16</number>
a–c
</figureCitation>
), and by the very thin, tapering posterior opisthomere process (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[757,785,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">pp</emphasis>
) (
<figureCitation box="[809,939,689,714]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 a – g" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[171,1417,489,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[169,1423,483,1688]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 16 a – g. Megaphyllum rhodopinum. Male from near Shabran Peak, Slavyanka Mt., Bulgaria: (16 a) gonopods, posterior view; (16 b) right gonopods, mesal view; (16 c) right opisthomere, meso-posterior view; (16 d) right opisthomere, lateral view. Males from near Proastio, Kavala county, Greece: penis form (16 e) posterior and (16 f) left lateral views, (16 f *) another penis, right lateral view. Female from the first locality: (16 g) left vulva, posterior view (setae omitted). Abbreviations: ah: anterior hump; ap: anterior process, asp: anterior process of the solenomere, ca: central ampulla, ct: connecting tube; h: hump, op: operculum, pa: posterior ampulla, pp: posterior process, psp: posterior process of the solenomere, P: promere. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223788/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
Figs 
<number box="[866,894,689,714]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="16.0">16</number>
a–b
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,509,1038]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
Opisthomere’s (
<figureCitation box="[377,560,725,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 a – g" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1730,1752]" captionTargetBox="[171,1417,489,1688]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[169,1423,483,1688]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 16 a – g. Megaphyllum rhodopinum. Male from near Shabran Peak, Slavyanka Mt., Bulgaria: (16 a) gonopods, posterior view; (16 b) right gonopods, mesal view; (16 c) right opisthomere, meso-posterior view; (16 d) right opisthomere, lateral view. Males from near Proastio, Kavala county, Greece: penis form (16 e) posterior and (16 f) left lateral views, (16 f *) another penis, right lateral view. Female from the first locality: (16 g) left vulva, posterior view (setae omitted). Abbreviations: ah: anterior hump; ap: anterior process, asp: anterior process of the solenomere, ca: central ampulla, ct: connecting tube; h: hump, op: operculum, pa: posterior ampulla, pp: posterior process, psp: posterior process of the solenomere, P: promere. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/223788/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
Figs 
<number box="[435,462,725,750]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="16.0">16</number>
a–b, 
<number box="[517,545,725,750]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="16.0">16</number>
d
</figureCitation>
) posterior process (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[784,812,726,749]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">pp</emphasis>
) slender, apically pointed, shorter than the solenomere. The finger-like anterior solenomere process (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[662,700,762,785]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">asp</emphasis>
) longer than the posterior one (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1062,1101,762,785]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">psp</emphasis>
). Apical posterior hump (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1397,1426,761,786]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">ph</emphasis>
) hardly distinguishable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,509,1038]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
Uniformly brown animals, with no dorsal longitudinal lines. Body length and height: males: 
<quantity box="[1273,1431,833,858]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.685" metricValueMax="3.25" metricValueMin="2.12" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" unit="mm" value="26.85" valueMax="32.5" valueMin="21.2">21.2–32.5mm</quantity>
, 
<quantity box="[151,281,869,894]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" unit="mm" value="1.9" valueMax="2.2" valueMin="1.6">1.6–2.2mm</quantity>
; females: 
<quantity box="[395,532,869,894]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.87" metricValueMax="4.2" metricValueMin="3.54" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" unit="mm" value="38.7" valueMax="42.0" valueMin="35.4">35.4–42mm</quantity>
, 
<quantity box="[543,675,870,894]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.15" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" unit="mm" value="3.15" valueMax="3.4" valueMin="2.9">2.9–3.4mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="85" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,509,1038]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,905,930]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is known only from the eastern parts of the Balkan Peninsula. Nearly a decade after the original description (Verhoeff 
<number box="[499,556,942,966]" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" value="1928.0">1928</number>
) Verhoeff lowered 
<taxonomicName box="[782,918,941,965]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Megaphyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="30" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhodopinum">
<emphasis box="[782,918,941,965]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="85">rhodopinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
